flowchart LR

  subgraph WHY["1. Why this group exists"]
    W1["The platform cannot stop at all the other planes worked"]
    W2["It also has to prove that the run can be operated, observed, reconstructed, governed, closed, idled, and cost-accounted for with the same rigor as execution itself"]
    W3["The operations, governance, and meta definition says the platform only counts as a serious operational system when it can be operated, audited, governed, and economically managed"]
    W4["That means no hidden drift, no fake receipts, no missing evidence, no unbounded spend, and no unverifiable verdicts"]
  end

  subgraph PATHS["2. Why the six paths are justified together"]
    P1["Run reconstruction and receipt closure path"]
    P2["Governance append and close-marker path"]
    P3["Proof-matrix and final-verdict publication path"]
    P4["Drift-visible observability attestation path"]
    P5["Idle-safe teardown and residual-readability path"]
    P6["Cost guardrail and cost-to-outcome closure path"]
    P7["Run reconstruction proves earlier lane receipts become an exact run story rather than a hand-assembled summary"]
    P8["Governance append and close-marker proves reconstructed closure truth is formally appended and marked closed under run scope rather than merely described"]
    P9["Proof-matrix and final-verdict publication proves whole-platform judgment is explicit: full source matrix blocker-free, six-proof matrix complete, and final verdict published"]
    P10["Drift-visible observability attestation proves live visibility is tied to the actual active runtime path, with freshness, alert coverage, and drift detection treated as closure truths rather than tooling decoration"]
    P11["Idle-safe teardown and residual-readability proves full-platform closure is not enough; the system must also stop safely, leave no forbidden residuals behind, and keep evidence readable after teardown"]
    P12["Cost guardrail and cost-to-outcome closure proves post-run spend is attributable, budgeted, and tied to explicit proof and risk-retirement outcomes rather than left as vague cloud billing"]
    P13["Taken together, the six paths prove Group 7 is a bounded closure system with six distinct owned outcomes rather than the dashboards and cleanup part"]
  end

  subgraph CLAIM["3. Group-level claim"]
    G1["The platform turns execution closure into governed, observable, auditable, idle-safe, and cost-accountable run truth"]
    G2["The current wired system can be reconstructed exactly, judged explicitly, drift-checked live, shut down safely, and economically accounted for"]
    G3["That makes the system look like a real operational meta-layer rather than work merely happening and later being described"]
  end

  subgraph PROOF["4. What this group proves for A"]
    A1["Strongest closure: completeness, continuity, and safety"]
    A2["Completeness closes because the run-close and final-phase rules require run reconstruction plus governance closure, whole-platform judgment with complete source and proof matrices, and teardown, residual, readability, and cost closure before the run is fully closed"]
    A3["Continuity closes because Group 7 ties all prior planes into one exact run story and then carries that story through reconciliation, governance append, final verdict publication, teardown and readability, and cost-to-outcome closure"]
    A4["That continuity is reinforced by the design authority too: every lane must produce deploy, monitor, fail, recover, rollback, and cost-control proof, and no full verdict is valid without that six-part set"]
    A5["Safety closes because the whole group is fail-closed on incomplete matrices, verdict inconsistency, residual cost risk, unreadable evidence after teardown, unattributed spend, and drift between live runtime and the declared active path"]
    A6["It also gives strong existence closure because these are materially seated in real reporter and reconciliation lanes, real governance append and closure-marker surfaces, real final-phase closure lanes for matrices, verdict publication, teardown, readability, and cost closure, and pinned observability and cost-control surfaces"]
  end

  subgraph AMBIG["5. A ambiguities to carry upward"]
    M1["The main A ambiguity is explanatory"]
    M2["We need to keep very clear the difference between run reconstruction truth, formal governance closure, whole-platform verdict truth, live observability attestation, idle-safe closure, and cost accountability"]
    M3["The design intentionally separates these, but an outsider could easily collapse them into one vague operations and reporting story if we synthesize lazily"]
    M4["There is also one current-wired nuance to state honestly: some cost capture remains explicitly scoped rather than pretending to be universally complete"]
    M5["The registry keeps cost-capture scope and defer reasons explicit rather than faking full billing coverage, and that honesty is part of the design rather than a weakness"]
  end

  subgraph PARK["6. Bi spillover to park"]
    B1["Questions about dashboard freshness and alert behavior under longer or noisier pressure, teardown and readability after repeated long-run cycles, cost envelopes under fuller operational cadence, and drift attestation across broader coupled proofs belong later in Bi"]
    B2["For A, Group 7 only needs to prove that the current wired platform has a real meta-layer for reconstruction, governance closure, final judgment, observability attestation, safe idling, and spend accountability"]
  end

  subgraph VERDICT["7. Group verdict"]
    V1["Group 7 proves that the platform does not merely run and stop; it closes itself as a governed operational system"]
    V2["This is a major A win because the current wired system has a genuine operational closure architecture: not just dashboards, receipts, budgets, or teardown scripts, but explicit truths for run reconstruction, formal closure, final judgment, live visibility, safe idling, and cost-to-outcome accountability"]
  end

